		<h1 class="entry-title">SCOTTISH SECULAR SOCIETY PRESENTING RAIF BADAWI WITH ANNUAL AIKENHEAD AWARD</h1>
		<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="entry-date"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20150107184157/http://www.scottishsecularsociety.com/scottish-secular-society-presenting-raif-badawi-with-annual-aikenhead-award/" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2015-01-03T23:01:04+00:00">January 3, 2015</time></a></span> <span class="byline"><span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20150107184157/http://www.scottishsecularsociety.com/author/Admin/" rel="author">Garry Otton</a></span></span>			<span class="comments-link"><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20150107184157/http://www.scottishsecularsociety.com/scottish-secular-society-presenting-raif-badawi-with-annual-aikenhead-award/#comments" title="Comment on SCOTTISH SECULAR SOCIETY PRESENTING RAIF BADAWI WITH ANNUAL AIKENHEAD AWARD">2 Comments</a></span>
					</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
	</header><!-- .entry-header -->

		<div class="entry-content">
		<p><strong> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20150107184157/http://www.scottishsecularsociety.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/raif2.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2003" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20150107184157im_/http://www.scottishsecularsociety.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/raif2.jpg" alt="raif2" width="720" height="405"/></a></strong><em>Raif Badawi</em></p>
<p>SCOTTISH SECULAR SOCIETY<strong> PRESENTING RAIF BADAWI WITH ANNUAL AIKENHEAD AWARD</strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
<li>Raif Badawi is convicted of ‘liberal thoughts’ and blasphemy in Saudi Arabia</li>
<li>Badawi is expected to be lashed on Friday</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Raif Badawi, who celebrates his 30<sup>th</sup> birthday on 13 January, was arrested in Jeddah (Saudi Arabia) in June 2012. On July 29, 2013 after he was convicted under Saudi Arabia’s Anti-Cybercrime Law of <em>“founding a liberal website…. adopting liberal thought”</em> and for <em>“insulting Islam”</em>. He was sentenced to 600 lashes and seven years and three months in prison.</p>
<p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20150107184157/http://www.scottishsecularsociety.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/raif.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2004" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20150107184157im_/http://www.scottishsecularsociety.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/raif.jpg" alt="raif" width="720" height="540"/></a></p>
<p><em>Raif Badawi in George Square, Glasgow</em></p>
<p>Raif Badawi is now facing 10 years in prison, 1,000 lashes and a fine of 1 million Saudi riyals.</p>
<p>In December 2013, Raif Badawi, founder of the website “Saudi Arabian Liberals” which he formed to create an online liberal forum in Saudi Arabia, appealed to his initial sentence of 600 lashes and seven years and three months in prison to the District Court in Jeddah. In response, in May 2014, Jeddah’s Criminal Court sentenced Badawi to 10 years in prison, 1,000 lashes and a fine of 1million Saudi riyals (approx. £170,000) on charges of <em>“insulting Islam”</em> and <em>“founding a liberal website&#8221;</em>. The court also sentenced him to a 10-year travel ban and 10-year ban from participating in visual, electronic and written media, both to be applied following his release. Some reports (we are checking on the accuracy of these) say he is diabetic, which would make wound treatment more difficult. It is unclear what quality medical attention he is receiving.</p>
<p>On 30 October 2014, a source following Raif&#8217;s case in the Saudi kingdom, who asked to remain anonymous, informed Scottish Secular Society Vice Chair, Ramin Forghani that the Saudi interior ministry had sanctioned implementation of the verdict against Raif Badawi and sent it to prison administrators for enforcement.</p>
<p>Badawi’s lawyer, Waleed Abu Al-Khair, a human rights activist, was also arrested on 15th of April 2014 and in June 2014. He was sentenced to 15 years in jail for charges including <em>“undermining the regime and officials”</em>. He is one of a number of lawyers with interest in human rights protection who have recently faced charges in consequence of advocating human rights in Saudi Arabia.</p>
<p>Raif Badawi won the 2014 One Humanity Award of PEN Canada and Ensaf Haidar, his wife, who lives in exile with their three children, received the award on his behalf. On being notified that her husband had been awarded the PEN prize, she quoted a line from his Twitter feed: <em>“We want life for those who wish death to us; and we want rationality for those who want ignorance for us.”</em></p>
<p>According to the last news, on 31 December Raif Badawi was transported to a new prison, Al Islahia in Jeddah. It is a move that paves the way for the execution of his penalty, including the lashings which are expected to start on Friday 9<sup>th</sup> January.<sup>1 </sup>The decision to execute Badawi’s penalty was signed by the interior minister, Mohammad bin Naif.</p>
<p>Scottish Secular Society Vice Chair, Ramin Forghani said today: <em>“Raif&#8217;s situation is a clear violation of human rights by Saudi authorities. The Saudi Arabian government is a member of United Nations Human Rights Council and should answer to the international community about this matter and cease implementation of the verdict.”</em></p>
<p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20150107184157/http://www.scottishsecularsociety.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Aikenhead-award.jpg"><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-2005" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20150107184157im_/http://www.scottishsecularsociety.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Aikenhead-award.jpg" alt="Aikenhead award" width="954" height="438"/></a></p>
<p><em>Aikenhead award</em></p>
<p>In awarding Raif Badawi the Aikenhead award, which is the Scottish Secular Society’s inaugural annual award for commitment to secular values, SSS Chair, Spencer Fildes, said today: <em>“The world should be outraged at this assault on a man’s liberty. We should remember that here in Scotland we prosecuted and hung a 20-year-old Edinburgh student Thomas Aikenhead for blasphemy in 1697 with the full support of the Church of Scotland. This is uniting the world in its support for common humanity and compassion. The SSS invites readers to join Amnesty International’s letter-writing campaign<sup>4 </sup>urging clemency.”</em></p>
<p>The award is a sculpture showing fingers appearing through granite and was designed by sculptor, Sandeha Lynch. It was scheduled to be awarded in Raif Badawi’s absence in February after waxes were cast for the foundry but the recent announcement of Badawi’s lashings have pre-empted this and the Scottish Secular Society are now making an urgent statement and sending a cheque to his wife.</p>
<p>ENDS</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Notes to Editors: &#8211;</p>
<ol>
<li>The article states that the lashing will take place in front of Aljefali mosque in Jeddah but doesn’t mention a source for this information.</li>
</ol>
